 Rainbow GitHub - An introduction to the DOM

Intro

GitHub squares are boring:

First, we'll make ourselves look l33t!

Next, we'll add some colour:

Finally, we'll make it dance!

Introduction to the DOM (Document Object Model)

The HTML you write is parsed by the browser and turned into the DOM. We can interact with the DOM using JavaScript!

Open a new tab, head to Google and open up developer tools. Go to the Console tab. We can write JavaScript here.

Try running:

document // you'll get back the entire HTML
document.body // you'll get back the <body> part of the HTML

We can manipulate with these elements, let's add a CSS border:

document.body.style.border = '30px solid red'

If you want to select a specific element, you can use querySelector and pass in a CSS style selector, e.g.:

document.querySelector('#sfdiv') // returns the #sfdiv element (Google's search box container)
document.querySelector('#sfdiv').style.border = '1px solid red' // sets a red border on the search box container

Inspect the #sfdiv element in dev tools, you'll see some CSS has been added! 

If you want to select multiple elements, you can use querySelectorAll, e.g:

document.querySelectorAll('input[type=submit]') // returns an array of all the submit buttons

Let's loop through this array of submit buttons and change their background colours:

document.querySelectorAll('input[type=submit]').forEach(function (item) {
  // for each submit button (called item)
  item.style.background = 'red'
})

You can see the other handy methods here: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document

Inspecting GitHub's DOM

Open a new tab and head to your GitHub profile page. With developer tools open, click the inspect icon. Move your cursor around the squares to check out the DOM.

You can see the box of squares is an SVG element with the class js-calendar-graph-svg. Inside the element, there is a group (<g>). Inside that group are columns, which are also groups (<g>). Finally, inside those are the actual squares! (<rect>)

We can access the entire SVG with:

document.querySelector('.js-calendar-graph-svg')

We can access each column with:

document.querySelectorAll('.js-calendar-graph-svg g g') // note: we want every column (which is a group inside every group)

Challenge - All Green

You should have the tools you need to proceed with the challenge. Only use the hints if you get stuck!

  1. In console, find all the columns and loop through them.
    document.querySelectorAll('.js-calendar-graph-svg g g').forEach(function (column) {
  console.log('column!');
})
  2. Now that you have each column, find and loop through each columns squares (rect).
    document.querySelectorAll('.js-calendar-graph-svg g g').forEach(function (column) {
  column.querySelectorAll('rect').forEach(function (square) {
    console.log('square!');
  })
})
  3. Use the setAttribute method to set each square's fill value to green.
    document.querySelectorAll('.js-calendar-graph-svg g g').forEach(function (column) {
  column.querySelectorAll('rect').forEach(function (square) {
    square.setAttribute('fill', '#7bc96f');
  })
})

Beast Mode - Rainbow


  1. Instead of setting every square to green, see if you can make a random colour. Using rgb instead of a hexcode will make this easier. You might need to Google how to generate a random number in JS.
    var r = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1; // max value can be 255
var g = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1;
var b = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1;
var rgb = [r, g, b];
item.setAttribute('fill', 'rgb(' + rgb.join(',') + ')');
  2. Check out JavaScript's setInterval method. Can you make the squares change colour every few seconds?

    setInterval(function(){
 document.querySelectorAll('.js-calendar-graph-svg g g').forEach(function (column) {
    column.querySelectorAll('rect').forEach(function (item) {
      var r = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1;
      var g = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1;
      var b = Math.floor(Math.random() * 255) + 1;
      var rgb = [r, g, b];
      item.setAttribute('fill', 'rgb(' + rgb.join(',') + ')');
    })
  })
}, 500)

You made it!
